            <!-- Contents -->
            <noteGrp type="workDesc">
               <note type="description">Commentaries on the 99 Divine Names of God. After a brief
                     introduction in which the traditional theological categories of the Names are
                     laid out, the 99 Names of God (as in al-Ghazālī’s listing) are treated
                     according to three concepts (first proposed by Abū Madyan): taʿalluq
                     (dependence); taḥaqquq (realisation); and takhalluq (assimilation). Critical
                     edition and Spanish translation by P. Beneito.</note>
               <note type="structure"/>
               <note type="contentsNote"/>
            </noteGrp>
            <!-- Stemmatics -->
            <note type="stemmatics">OY lists 22 mss., although none can be considered truly
                  historic. However, the evidence is compelling: Ulu Cami 1581 (c.826H) may have
                  been copied from an original, as it carries a note by IA about the composition of
                  the work, that it was written in Ramaḍān 621H for a known disciple, Sharafuddīn
                  Abū Muḥammad ʿAbd al-Wāḥid b. Abū Bakr b. Sulaymān al-Ḥamawī. The earliest copy is
                  Fatih 5298, dated 783H, which also has a colophon saying that it is a work by IA
                  and that it was dictated to a student in 621H in Damascus. A work of this title is
                  listed in both the lists which IA made of his own works, Fihris muʾallafāt
                  al-shaykh al-akbar (RG142) and Ijāza l-il-malik al-Muẓaffar (RG 269), and there is
                  a correspondence with other works on the Divine Names (see FM 559).</note>
